Product name: Antique Victorian Silver Locket with Assyrian Winged Lamassu Lion in Relief
Description:
Antique Victorian sterling silver locket with a winged Assyrian lion on the front, dating to the later 1800's.
This is a highly unusual and stunning large locket, perfect for anyone with an interest in history!  The applied engraved relief on the front of the locket is an Assyrian Winged Lion with a human face, known as a Lamassu and possibly based on the example in the British museum.  In this case though the head is turned to face the viewer rather than being in profile, which is more usual for this figure.     The Lamassu was traditionally placed in a pair near or at the entrance to a throne room or other important location where it was viewed as being a protective figure.
The rear cover is plain, while inside both frames are intact (though degraded) with one glass window intact, as well as the original silk lining, which is a little worse for wear and could be replaced.  There are no dents or damage to the silver, only a slight 'dint' in one place on the rear cover.   The hinge is sound and works fine and the locket closes with a good click, holding securely.  The applied Lamassu on the front is held in place by three 'studs' which protrude through the front locket cover and are fixed in place by wire (recently replaced and secure).  Not hallmarked but tested as sterling silver.

Product name: Antique posy ring inscribed âA Hope Fulfilled. 18th March 1880â Victorian wedding band circa 1880.
Description:
A solid gold Victorian wedding band engraved to the interior in Italic script âA Hope Fulfilled. 18th March 1880â. Crafted in 18ct gold circa 1880. Weight 4.75g
Measurements: UK ring size N Â½ , US ring size 7. Width of band 4mm.
History
This piece was made circa 1880 during the Victorian era, a period in English history defined by the reign of Queen Victoria, from 1837 to 1901. Posy rings, on which a romantic verse was engraved within the band, are first seen in the 12th century but were highly popular as betrothal or wedding rings in the 17th and 18th centuries. This Victorian wedding ring borrows from this tradition with a truly romantic message of requited love, a classic antique wedding ring with a romantic history.

Product name: Victorian Hand Brooch Bog Oak Hand Holding Wreath of Roses and Wheat Symbolic Brooch
Description:
Victorian hand brooch made of bog oak which originates from the peat bogs in Ireland. The hand image was very popular in Victorian jewelry from approx 1860-1890.  Depending on what images are with it, would often determine it's meaning.  This one has the hand holding a wreath of roses. The roses symbolize love and the wreath was symbolic of hope and eternal life.  The hand is also holding wheat sheaves. Nicely detailed.
Bog oak was used as on of many black materials during the Victorian era. It is easier to tell because it has some brown coloring and has a bit of a woody texture. 
This one is a bit larger in size than some. It measures 3" x 1 1/4".
The condition is good - it has survived the past century very well. There are no chips, cracks or problems. The brooch has a C-style pin clasp which is sturdy and in working order.
A wonderful piece to wear and a lovely addition for your collection...
Enjoy!

Product name: Rhinestone Cat Eye Glasses Cateye Eyeglasses NOS Vintage Mink
Description:
GENERAL
Beautiful New Old Stock Vintage Women's Cat eye glasses frames. They were never worn and are in mint condition. They are made in France by Selecta Optical. For more New Old Stock never used Vintage cat eye glasses, check out my Ebay store for a large selection.
CONDITION
These are New Old stock and were never worn. We have inspected them to make sure they are fully functional, can take your prescription lenses in them and are suitable for daily wear. They have been sitting in a box all these years and may need some adjustment by an optician before use.
SIZE
Width, between hinges: 4 7/8 inches
Temple Length: 5 1/2 inches
Lens Width: 44mm
Bridge: 22mm
This is a medium vintage size.
Most Vintage frames tend to run small. They were worn much closer to the face than today's frames. Cat eye glasses are no exception. While there are many factors affecting the size, the lens width is a good way to get a general idea. Lens size 42 and lower is considered small, 44 and 46 medium, 48 and above are large. Please make sure this size will work for you before ordering.
STYLE
Cat-eye glasses are a form of eyewear for women that were mainly popular in the 1950's and 1960's among fashionable women. Out of the small amount that were originally made, most are not around today and they are becoming harder to find. When you buy a pair of vintage cat eye glasses, you are not just getting something made yesterday and shipped overseas. You are wearing something that has been through life, an age different than our own, and survived till this day. Wearing vintage cat eye glasses assures that youâll stand out from the masses in a pair of glasses that brings out your individuality. 
PAYMENT
We accept Paypal only. Payment is generally expected within 7 days. If you need longer please notify us.
Returns are accepted within 14 days of delivery. We offer a money back guarantee if there was a mistake on our part or something was described wrong. Otherwise, store credit will be given for the purchase of any pair we sell of similar or lesser value.
SHIPPING
Shipping in the US is with USPS first class mail.
We usually ship within 1 business day, so it should take about a week for your Eyeglasses to arrive, sometimes faster.
We ship to anywhere in the world with USPS First Class Mail International. Shipping cost is a flat rate of 8. Please note that USPS First classes Mail does not have tracking. It generally takes 2-3 weeks to arrive. If you prefer faster shipping with tracking Please select the USPS priority worldwide option.
ABOUT US
We are a New York based Company specializing in Vintage and Antique eyeglass frames. We currently have 1000's of vintage and antique eyeglass frames in stock. We have a large selection of Vintage New Old Stock Cat eye glasses frames, as well as 100's of Round Windsor eyeglass frames. We also have a large selection of Pince-nez, Rimless, and pretty much anything made from 1850-1970. Check out our Ebay store to see our other frames. 
Our goal is to bring you the best selection of quality, vintage frames. Unless a pair is New Old Stock, normal wear and tear is expected as these frames have been used or have been sitting around for many years. Each pair of vintage frames we sell is inspected to make sure it can handle new lenses and is suitable for everyday wear, exceptions will be noted. Thank you for shopping with us, We hope you enjoy your Vintage frames.

American Button MachinesÂ® in an Authorized distributor for Tecre Co, Inc button machines and supplies. We are huge fans of the Etsy marketplace and due to popular demand, decided to open our own Etsy store to give our customers one more avenue to purchase button making supplies. 
We only sell brand new authentic Tecre button machines and paper cutters. All of our pinback button making supplies are proudly âMade in the USAâ and conform to the strictest US industry standard sizes. 
PLEASE NOTE: There are a lot of manufacturers that make proprietary sized buttons or they are manufactured outside the USA and do not conform to the US industry standard sizes. If you are unsure of what button machine you have or if our parts will work, please contact us before ordering. We are happy to help you (thatâs what makes our day complete!) find the correct sized buttons for your equipment.
We do NOT sell 1.25â, 2.25â or 3â Badge-a-Minit (BAM) sized button machines and their parts will not fit Tecre brand button makers that are made in the USA. Likewise, our button supplies will not work with BAM button machines or button machines that are made in China. 
Unless you have a photo button machine or photo punch, we recommend using a 24lb bond paper with a brightness of at least 100. If you use a thicker paper, you run the risk of jamming your machine or slightly deforming the buttons on the smaller sized buttons.

The paper circle is always larger than the finished button because the paper wraps and crimps around the back of the button.
